    <p><h3>Adding New Cards:</h3></p>
      <p><iframe width="640" height="480" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/f100H9W2zg8" frameborder="1" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
      <p><h3>Adding New Cards:</h3></p>
      <h5>(Text Version)</h5>
      <p>If you don’t yet have the Khmer font installed on your computer, I recommend you look at the resource which tells you how to do so, and input at the very least both the Khmer and your own transliteration in your deck.  From this point it is really very simple, you simply type in an English word in the box that says <b>‘front’</b>, and then type in the Khmer translation in the box that says <b>‘back’</b>.  As you do this, 2 cards will be created, meaning that you will be tested on translating from both <b>English to Khmer</b>, and also <b>Khmer to English.</b></p>
      <p>Now you can add cards as and when you feel like doing so.  Depending on the size of your deck, there are some options you might want to change. The default setting is to allow you to study <b>20</b> new cards a day (which will work out as <b>10</b> new words), and a maximum of <b>100</b> cards each day.  This is great for when you are first starting out, but when you are working with bigger decks, this is going to be restrictive.  So lets learn how to change these settings.</p>
      <p>First open up the deck you want to change and then click <b>‘options’.</b>  Once you have done this you will be under the <b>‘New Cards’</b> tab. Here you can alter the new cards/day, and this will let you study more of the new cards you have just added in one time.  If you are like me, you may save up new words until the weekend, and then sit down and type <b>50</b> odd words into your deck.  This will give you <b>100</b> new cards to study, and so it may be worth increasing the number of new cards/day to 40, meaning you are testing yourself on <b>20</b> new words each day.</p><br><br><br>
